.SS "Server mode"
.sp
jome features a server mode to avoid creating a process (a Qt window can
be quite long to create) every time you need to pick an emoji. With this
mode, you can view the jome window instantaneously.
.sp
To start jome in server mode, use the \fB\-s\fP\~option to specify the
server name:
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
$ jome \-s mein\-server
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
.sp
This creates a local server named \fBmein\-server\fP. On Unix, it creates
the socket file \fB/tmp/mein\-server\fP.
.if n .sp
.RS 4
.it 1 an-trap
.nr an-no-space-flag 1
.nr an-break-flag 1
.br
.ps +1
.B Important
.ps -1
.br
.sp
On Unix, the server mode won\(cqt work if the socket file
already exists. Remove the file before you start jome in server mode:
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
$ rm \-f /tmp/mein\-server
$ jome \-s mein\-server
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
.sp .5v
.RE
.sp
When jome starts in server mode, it doesn\(cqt show its window. Instead,
it waits for a command sent by the client, \fBjome\-ctl\fP(1). To show the
window:
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
$ jome\-ctl mein\-server
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
.sp
When you accept an emoji, \fBjome\-ctl\fP(1) prints what jome also prints
to the standard output and quits with exit code\~0. Therefore, the
options passed to \fBjome\fP(1) control the output
format of \fBjome\-ctl\fP(1).
.sp
If you cancel jome (press \fBEscape\fP or \fBCtrl\fP+\fBC\fP, or close the
window), \fBjome\-ctl\fP(1) prints nothing and returns with exit
code\~1.
.sp
In server mode, jome doesn\(cqt quit once you accept an emoji or cancel: it
hides the window and keeps listening. To make it quits gracefully, which
also removes the socket file:
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
$ jome\-ctl mein\-server quit
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
.sp
You don\(cqt need to use what \fBjome\-ctl\fP(1) prints to the standard
output. You can use jome in server mode with the \fB\-c\fP\~option to
make jome execute a command itself. For example:
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
$ rm \-f /tmp/mein\-server
$ jome \-s mein\-server \-c \*(Aqxdotool type\*(Aq
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
.sp
Then, bind a keyboard shortcut to:
.sp
.if n .RS 4
.nf
.fam C
$ jome\-ctl mein\-server
.fam
.fi
.if n .RE
.SS "Type the accepted emoji"
.sp
Here are Bash scripts to type the accepted emoji with \fBxdotool\fP(1).
.sp
